<h2>HVAC Systems in Washington</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Washington's diverse climate zones require different HVAC approaches depending on location and specific home needs. Western Washington's marine climate features mild summers with temperatures rarely exceeding 80¬∞F and moderate winters averaging 35-45¬∞F, making heating the primary concern. Air conditioning needs are minimal, with most homes requiring cooling only 10-20 days annually. For these areas, heat pumps with SEER ratings of 14-16 and HSPF ratings of 8.5-10 provide optimal efficiency and comfort.</p>

<p>Eastern Washington experiences a more continental climate with hot, dry summers reaching 85-95¬∞F and cold winters dropping to 20-30¬∞F. These areas benefit from higher SEER ratings of 16-20 for cooling efficiency and robust heating capabilities. Dual-fuel systems combining heat pumps with gas furnace backup are popular in these regions, providing efficient operation across extreme temperature ranges while maintaining comfort and minimizing operating costs.</p>

<p>Modern heat pump technology has revolutionized HVAC efficiency in Washington's climate. Cold-climate heat pumps can effectively heat homes even when outdoor temperatures drop below 0¬∞F, making them viable throughout the state. These systems typically achieve 200-300% efficiency compared to traditional electric resistance heating, resulting in substantial energy savings. Variable-speed compressors and advanced refrigerants further enhance performance, allowing precise temperature control and reduced energy consumption during partial-load conditions.</p>

