<h2>Washington Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Washington offers several attractive incentives for solar and HVAC upgrades, making these investments more accessible for homeowners. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, permits, and interconnection fees. For a typical \$20,000 solar system, homeowners can claim a \$6,000 federal tax credit, significantly reducing the effective cost.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> The most significant incentive available, covering 30% of total solar system costs including panels, inverters, batteries, installation labor, permits, and interconnection fees. This credit can be carried forward if it exceeds tax liability in the installation year, and there's no maximum limit on the credit amount.</li>
<li><strong>State Sales Tax Exemption:</strong> Washington provides a 100% sales tax exemption for solar energy systems, saving homeowners approximately 8-10% on equipment costs. This exemption applies to residential solar panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and batteries, typically saving \$1,500-3,000 on average installations.</li>
<li><strong>Puget Sound Energy Solar Programs:</strong> PSE offers net metering allowing customers to receive retail rate credits for excess solar production. The utility also provides interconnection support and streamlined approval processes for residential solar installations under 25kW capacity.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Programs:</strong> Many Washington utilities offer rebates for high-efficiency heat pumps and smart thermostats. Snohomish County PUD provides up to \$1,200 rebates for qualifying heat pump installations, while Clark Public Utilities offers \$500-800 rebates for ENERGY STAR certified systems.</li>
<li><strong>Maximizing Incentives:</strong> To maximize savings, homeowners should coordinate solar and HVAC upgrades to take advantage of multiple programs simultaneously. Installing solar and heat pump systems in the same tax year allows claiming federal credits for solar while accessing utility rebates for HVAC improvements, potentially reducing total project costs by 25-35%.</li>
</ul>

